# HawkView phase 2 — Microsoft OAuth + tenant connection
# Activate this rule when working on: microsoft/, tenants/, or any Graph API task.

## Phase 2 goal
Allow an MSP to connect a Microsoft 365 tenant to HawkView via OAuth admin consent.
Store the connection securely. Verify it works. Nothing more yet.

## What done looks like for phase 2
- [ ] Tenant model in Prisma with encrypted token storage
- [ ] GET  /microsoft/auth/url?tenantId=  → returns Azure consent URL
- [ ] GET  /microsoft/auth/callback        → handles redirect, stores tokens
- [ ] POST /tenants                        → create tenant record
- [ ] GET  /tenants                        → list tenants for current user
- [ ] GET  /tenants/:id                    → get single tenant
- [ ] DELETE /tenants/:id                  → disconnect tenant
- [ ] GET  /tenants/:id/status             → verify Graph API token is valid
- [ ] GraphService.getClient(tenantId)     → returns authenticated Graph client

## Prisma schema additions for phase 2
Add to schema.prisma:

model Tenant {
  id           String    @id @default(uuid())
  displayName  String
  microsoftTenantId String @unique
  userId       String
  user         User      @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id])
  accessToken  String    # encrypt at rest — see encryption rule below
  refreshToken String    # encrypt at rest
  tokenExpiresAt DateTime
  scopes       String[]
  connectedAt  DateTime  @default(now())
  updatedAt    DateTime  @updatedAt
  isActive     Boolean   @default(true)
}

Also add to User model:
  tenants Tenant[]

## Token encryption rule — CRITICAL
Never store Microsoft OAuth tokens as plain text in the database.
Use AES-256-GCM encryption via Node.js crypto module.
Create: common/utils/crypto.util.ts with encrypt(text) and decrypt(text).
Key comes from env var: ENCRYPTION_KEY (32-byte hex string).
Add ENCRYPTION_KEY to env.validation.ts as required string.

## Azure app registration requirements
The HawkView app needs these API permissions (application permissions, not delegated):
  - User.Read.All            (list users + MFA state)
  - UserAuthenticationMethod.Read.All  (MFA methods per user)
  - AuditLog.Read.All        (sign-in logs)
  - Directory.Read.All       (tenant directory info)

Admin consent is REQUIRED for all of these. The OAuth flow must use:
  - response_type: code
  - scope: https://graph.microsoft.com/.default
  - prompt: admin_consent
  - response_mode: query

Env vars needed:
  AZURE_CLIENT_ID=
  AZURE_CLIENT_SECRET=
  AZURE_REDIRECT_URI=http://localhost:3000/microsoft/auth/callback

## Graph API client pattern
// microsoft/graph.service.ts
// getClient(tenantId) should:
// 1. Load tenant from DB by tenantId
// 2. Decrypt access token
// 3. Check if expired — if yes, refresh using Microsoft token endpoint
// 4. Save new tokens to DB (encrypted)
// 5. Return a configured axios instance (or @microsoft/microsoft-graph-client)
// Never make raw Graph API calls outside GraphService.

## Microsoft OAuth token refresh
Token endpoint: https://login.microsoftonline.com/{tenant}/oauth2/v2.0/token
Body: grant_type=refresh_token, refresh_token, client_id, client_secret, scope
Store new access + refresh tokens (encrypted) back to DB on every refresh.
If refresh fails (token revoked): set tenant.isActive = false, return 401 with code TENANT_AUTH_EXPIRED.

## Multi-tenant isolation rules (repeat from backend.mdc — critical here)
- Every tenant query MUST filter by userId (current JWT user) AND tenantId.
- Never return a tenant record without verifying it belongs to req.user.id.
- Pattern for all tenant service methods:
  this.prisma.tenant.findFirstOrThrow({ where: { id: tenantId, userId: user.id } })
  // throws if not found OR if it belongs to another user

## Error codes for phase 2
TENANT_NOT_FOUND          - tenant doesn't exist or doesn't belong to user
TENANT_ALREADY_CONNECTED  - microsoftTenantId already registered
TENANT_AUTH_EXPIRED       - MS refresh token invalid, user must reconnect
OAUTH_STATE_MISMATCH      - CSRF check failed on callback
OAUTH_EXCHANGE_FAILED     - code→token exchange with Microsoft failed

## OAuth state / CSRF protection
Generate a random state param before redirecting to Microsoft.
Store it in a short-lived signed cookie or in-memory cache (Redis not needed yet — use NestJS CacheModule with memory store).
Verify it matches on callback before exchanging the code.
If mismatch: throw OAUTH_STATE_MISMATCH 400.

## Testing phase 2
Use a Microsoft 365 Developer Program tenant (free):
  https://developer.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-365/dev-program
Register the app at: https://portal.azure.com → App registrations
Use Graph Explorer to verify permissions before coding:
  https://developer.microsoft.com/en-us/graph/graph-explorer

Mock GraphService in unit tests — never make real Graph API calls in tests.
For e2e tests: mock the Microsoft token endpoint with nock or jest mocks.

## Module structure for phase 2
microsoft/
  microsoft.module.ts       # imports TenantsModule
  microsoft.controller.ts   # GET /microsoft/auth/url, GET /microsoft/auth/callback
  microsoft.service.ts      # OAuth flow: build URL, exchange code, store tokens
  graph.service.ts          # getClient(tenantId), wraps Graph API calls
  dto/
    connect-tenant.dto.ts   # { displayName: string }

tenants/
  tenants.module.ts
  tenants.controller.ts     # CRUD + status endpoint
  tenants.service.ts        # DB operations, always scoped to userId
  dto/
    create-tenant.dto.ts
    tenant-response.dto.ts  # never expose raw tokens in responses

## What NOT to build in phase 2
- Do not pull Graph API data yet (users, MFA, audit logs) — that is phase 3
- Do not build background sync jobs — phase 3
- Do not build reporting endpoints — phase 4
- Do not add multi-org support — future
- Keep it to: connect, store, verify, list, disconnect
